 -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJohn Doyle Klier’s pioneering publications on the relations between Jews and the Russian social order—on topics such as public opinion, governance, conversion, Russification politics, antisemitism, and pogroms—have influenced an entire generation of new scholarship. Jews in the East European Borderlands, a collection of essays honoring Klier’s life and work, brings together some of the most innovative scholarship in the field. Focusing on the complex, often violent, entanglements between Jews and Russians, historians and literary scholars critically reassess the artifacts of high culture, including Yiddish and Russian prose and poetry, as well as dimensions of daily life, including letter-writing, diaries, the work of philanthropy, photojournalism, and the mass circulation press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh1 aAvrutin, Eugene M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvrutin, Eugene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBudnitskii, Oleg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstraikh, Gennady, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrinberg, Marat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarlip, Joshua M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLitvak, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurav, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurav, Harriet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNakhimovsky, Alice, eco